'''''American Motorcycle Association v. Superior Court''''', {{law report|20|Cal. 3d|578}} (1978), was a case decided by the [[Supreme Court of California]] that first adopted a comparative fault regime for apportionment of [[legal liability|liability]] among multiple tortfeasors for [[negligence]] in California.<ref>[http://www.audiocasefiles.com/acf_cases/9050-american-motorcycle-association-v-superior-court Audio and summary of opinion at Audio Case Files]</ref>
